t shift to a service economy amidst worsening social and economic inequality. Through its cultural institutions, universities, banking, and corporate sectors, the municipality of São Paulo would become a world metropolis. At the same time, given its rapid growth from 2 million to 12 million residents in this period, São Paulo dealt with problems of distribution, housing, and governance. This significant volume elucidates these and other trends during the late twentieth and early twenty-first centuries, and will be an invaluable reference for scholars of history, policy, and the economy in Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIndustrieszBrazilzSão Paulo (State)xHistory. 0aService industrieszBrazilzSão Paulo (State)xHistory. 0aSocial changezBrazilzSão Paulo (State)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aAgriculture.  aAuto Industry.  aBrazil.  aClass.  aDemographic Transition.  aEconomic Development.  aFavelas.  aIndustrialization. Services.  aMetropolitan Regions.  aPolitical Change.  aRace.  aSocial Mobility.  aSão Paulo.1 aKlein, Herbert S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363184740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631847/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles